summary:
An embarrear endment of riches is an idiom that means an overabundance of something, or too much of a good thing, that originated in 1738 as John Ozells translation of a French play, LEmbarras des richesses 1726, by Lonor Jean Christine Soulas dAllainval.Example: All four of them have their own cars but theres no room in the drivewayan embarrear endment of riches.
The idiom has also inspired other works and been included in their titles. This includes: The Embarrear endment of Riches 1906, a play by Louis K. Anspacher, and a 1918 drama film of the same name based on the Anspacher play;
a 2006 music album of this name by Elephant Micah; the history lady pillowsk The Embarrear endment of Riches: An Interpretation of Dutch Culture in the Golden Age by Simon Schama; and An Embarrear endment of Riches, a 2000 novel written by Filipino author Charlson Ong.
